IT&rsquo;S a big week for SuperSport United!&nbsp;The three times league champions will play against the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) giants, TP Mazembe, and Soweto giants, Orlando Pirates, in the same week.&nbsp;On Tuesday night, Matsatsantsa a Pitori host Mazembe in the Caf Confederation Group D encounter at the Lucas Moripe stadium in Atteridgeville (7pm).Matsatsantsa will then turn their focus onto the Nedbank Cup final against Orlando Pirates at the Moses Mabhida Stadium in Durban on Saturday, in a repeat of last year&rsquo;s final (8.15pm).The Tshwane giants defeated Bucs 3-2 in a five goal thriller at last year&rsquo;s final in Polokwane, Limpopo.Matsatsantsa are equal on five points with the DRC outfit and Horoya of Guinea after three games, but top the group due to their superior goal difference.CF Mounana of Gabon are bottom of the table with no points.&nbsp;A win at home against the former African champions will edge them closer to the knockout stages.Matsatsantsa&rsquo;s teenage sensation, Teboho Mokoena, who scored in the 2-2 draw in the DRC two weeks ago, says he is looking forward to the two matches.&nbsp;The 19-year-old is hoping to feature in his first official domestic cup final after watching SuperSport lose 2-1 to Cape Town City in the Telkom Knockout decider in December.His proud mum Manthati and his aunt Mmatebogo will fly to Durban to cheer him on against Pirates, and he is hoping to make them proud.Mokoena said: &ldquo;I hope to feature in both games. Scoring against Mazembe in Congo was a dream come true. I was wearing a suit and sitting in the stands when we lost to Cape Town City in the first cup final, but now I hope to feature in the big game against Pirates.&ldquo;The preparations for both games have been going well, but first we have to focus on Mazembe.&nbsp;&ldquo;We know winning that game will increase our chances of going through to the knockout stages.&rdquo;Mokoena added that Matsatsantsa were looking to give coach Stuart Baxter, who jumped ship to Bafana Bafana, a fitting send-off by giving him a winner&rsquo;s medal.&nbsp;&ldquo;The biggest gift for our coach is the trophy and we&rsquo;ll fight hard for him. I hope this big week will end well for us,&rdquo; he said.Bucs have been playing friendlies to keep themselves fit for the final, while Caf matches have been keeping SuperSport busy.